## Root Causes & Fixes

### Bug 1 — Duplicate Processing (TOCTOU Race in `dequeue`)

**`job_queue.py:32-33`** — The `await asyncio.sleep(0.01)` was placed **before** `job["status"] = "processing"`. With 5 concurrent workers, all would see the job as `"pending"`, all suspend at the `await`, then all claim the same job — processing it 5 times.

**Fix:** Moved `job["status"] = "processing"` before the `await`, so the claim is recorded before any suspension point. Also wrapped the critical section in `async with self._lock` to serialize access across all workers.

### Bug 2 — Vanishing Failures (Missing `fail()` call)

**`worker.py:19-20`** — The `except` block printed the error but never called `queue.fail()`. Jobs that raised exceptions stayed stuck in `"processing"` status permanently — no retries, no "failed" state.

**Fix:** Added `queue.fail(job["id"], str(e))` so the queue manages retries (up to `max_retries`) and transitions to `"failed"` when exhausted.

### Concurrency Hardening

Added `asyncio.Lock()` to `JobQueue` (`job_queue.py:10, 32-37`) to serialize `dequeue()` operations, eliminating any remaining race window between the status check and the status assignment plus sleep. No public method signatures changed.
